### (1) Translation of the Story:

King Wu of Wei was discussing state affairs and was always correct in his judgments. None of his ministers could match him, and after the court session, he returned with a joyful expression. Wu Qi (a famous strategist and reformer) approached him and said, "Have you ever heard of the words of King Zhuang of Chu, which were reported to your courtiers?" King Wu of Wei replied, "What were King Zhuang of Chu's words?" Wu Qi responded, "King Zhuang of Chu was also discussing state affairs and was always correct in his judgments. None of his ministers could match him, and after the court session, he returned with a worried expression. Shen Gong Wu Chen asked him, 'Your Majesty, you have a worried expression after the court session. Why is that?' King Zhuang of Chu replied, 'When I discuss state affairs and am always correct, and none of my ministers can match me, I feel worried. This is because of the advice of Zhong Yi, who said: "The feudal lords who consider themselves worthy of learning from others will become kings, those who consider themselves worthy of making friends will become hegemons, those who consider themselves worthy of seeking advice will survive, and those who consider themselves worthy of planning but believe no one else is as capable as themselves will perish." Now, with my own unworthiness, and with no ministers able to match me, my state is nearly in danger of perishing. This is why I feel worried.' King Zhuang of Chu was worried because of this, but you, my lord, are joyful." King Wu of Wei hesitated, bowed twice, and said, "It is the will of Heaven that you, Master Wu Qi, reveal my faults."

